		<img width="2500" height="1200" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses-1536x737.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses-2048x983.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-artificial-shark-uteruses-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Scientists are getting better at keeping premature baby sharks alive in aquariums‚Äîa boon when captive sharks give birth early, or when aquariums receive donations of living shark fetuses taken from mothers that die in fishing nets. Photo by Papilio/Alamy Stock Photo</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Scientists Built an Artificial Shark Uterus</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">Preemie sharks that would otherwise die get by with a little help from a human-made womb.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/claudia-geib/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Claudia Geib</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						June 24, 2024 | 900 words, about 4 minutes
					</aside>

					
				</header>

				
